<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Faustus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Right now I have a windows box and a linux box (with slackware-current, it seemed to compile showeq just fine with the latest QT version) both connected to a Linksys 10/100 HUB and the cable modem to the Uplink port.  After reading a few backposts I read somewhere that the 10/100 Linksys hub can't be used with ShowEQ, so I was wondering if you could all please share which hubs you use successfully with ShowEQ if you have a similar setup to mine.  Any information would be greatly appreciated.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">k7</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">From what I've heard anything but a linksys 10/100.  Even an old linksys 10 would work (what I'm using).  People generally suggest a brand called netgear.  (Never even heard of netgear myself...)<P>Heh.  It seems the linksys 10/100's are more like switches than hubs.  Normally that is a good feature but...<P>Perhaps something that was straight 100 and not an autosensing...  I think the problem is when you have 10 and 10/100 connections on the same hub.  If you want you could try forcing all your nic's to 10.  Who knows?  Might work...</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Faustus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Both my NIC's currently are working at 100 right now so I don't really use the autosensing feature of the 10/100 Hub, someone just happened to give me that hub as a present.  Will try and look for the netgear brand, anyone know the specific model with an uplink port?  Or do most modern hubs have the uplink port?</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">CyberGlitch</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I am currently ussing a 8-port NetGear hub model number DS108 and it works great. got the hub for like $100 a few computer shows ago.<P>k7 - You've never heard of netgear I'm suprised. They're actualy a very good and reliable company. All my networking is netgear, NiC's and Hubs. I've never had a problem with them and will continue to use there products. Just my 2 cents.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Faustus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Will try and go over to my nearest BestBuy/whatever store tommorrow and see how it all goes with a Netgear hub.  Thanks for the model number CyberGlitch.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">WhiteFire</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Any true eathernet HUB will work.  What you have to watch out for is to make sure you do not get a switch.  Switches do not broadcast packets like HUBs do.  They route the information to the port that it needs to go to so other computers on the network never get a chance to read the information. <P>Hope this helps.<P>Whitefire</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Reality</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I am using a Linksys 10/100 and it works great the only reason it would not is if the EQ PC was on a different link speed than the Show Eq machine, both must be on 10 or 100.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Faustus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Really reality?  Both my machines run at 100 so they are on the same speeds, I don't know why my Linksys wouldn't work then?  What's the model number on your HUB?  I can't think of any reason why ShowEQ wouldn't be working, hrm.  Did you have to adjust anything specifically to get it to work?  My hub model is an EFAH05W and I'm pretty sure I've followed all network setup instructions to the letter... any information you could give me would be greatly appreciated.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">WhiteFire</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ok what to do if you are not getting Link Lights on your hub.....<P>1.  I konw it sounds stupid, but make sure the cables are plugged into the back of the Computers.<P>2.  Verify that the patch cables you have work.  Either use a cable tester or you can swap them with the patch cable another computer is using and see if you get a link light on the hub.<P>3.  Make sure you are not plugging your network cables into a special port on the hub.  Most hubs will have at least one port for an UPLINK, but I have seen some with other ports labled MID-X oor something like that.  Make sure you are not plugged into on of these ports.<P>4.  Windows ME and I think 98 SE looks for connection to a network on bootup.  If you are not plugged into the network on bootup it will disable the NIC card until you reboot your computer.  Make sure all cables are plugged in when you bootup.<P><BR>Whitefire</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Faustus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">The network is working fine and all is plugged in as should be whitefire, it works wonderfully in windows but for some reason I still can't see the packets going to my windows box with this hub ;(.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">casey</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">the problem people are experiencing with 10/100 hubs occurs when the EQ and SEQ box are using different speeds.  A hub works by just broadcasting the data everwhere, but you cant run it like that without a unique speed, and in _all_ 10/100 hubs, you realyl have 2 hubs, a 10mbit hub and a 100 mbit hub.  To communicate from one speed to another, the segments are switched, and that is why you cant sniff across different speeds, 100mbit ports only broadcast to other 100mbit ports, and likewise for 10mbit.<P>10/100's are fine, just make sure both boxes are operating atthe same speed.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Faustus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Is there a command in Linux to check if you are running at 100Mb?  I always assumed that I was since my NIC can handle 100Mb and windows always defaults to setting it up as a 100Mb, I don't see why Linux wouldn't do the same.  It's been a really frustrating struggle, if push comes to shove, perhaps the only solution is to buy a 10Mb only Hub and be done with it.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Faustus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well d'oh, I see they are both running at 100Mb according to the light on my hub *blush*, however, then this just makes it more confusing, it *should* be technically working since they are both running at 100Mb.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">WhiteFire</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Ok what you are going to have to do is set your NIC card in your Linux Box to PROMISC mode.  This can be done by typing "#ifconfig --promisc"<P>Whitefire</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Faustus</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I did that WhiteFire, I ended up buying a netgear 4 port 10Mb hub and it worked great from the get go... don't know why the Linksys doesn't work, though ;(.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">CSCMajor</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Buy the Netgear DS104. Costs 50 bucks, is dual speed and broadcasts packets on each port.  <IMG SRC="http://www.ethernalquest.org/ubb/smile.gif"></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
